<br>
Warriors are suck suck soloers, period.  We exchanged that in the name of balance by being GREAT group members.  <br>
<br>
Clerics are the same way, they are suck soloers, but they exchanged that for being GREAT group members.<br>
<br>
We gave something up to be more desired in a group, which was the inability to control our rate of experience gain without the explicit agreement of someone else to join with us.<br>
<br>
This is where one of the 3 biggest issues lies.  Where did the balance between good soloer vs. good group member go?<br>
<br>
Druid:  Quad kiting is boring, I hate medding, and I like grouping, therefore make me more group desirable.<br>
<br>
Answer SHOULD be:  &quot;Ok, but in return you have to give up the ability to quad kite, and therefore snare will only land on one target at a time, and coding will be introduced that you can only cast rain spells while grouped&quot;.<br>
<br>
Answer WAS:  OK, we'll increase your group desirablity by giving as a common spell drop, a group buff which is good HP/AC AND Mana regeneration, and by giving you better heals.<br>
<br>
This encroached on clerics who had a relatively &quot;safe&quot; position as one who exchanged utility for specialization.<br>
<br>
Clerics:  &quot;We're great in groups, but we can't solo even ONE experience producing mob without emptying our manabar and having massive downtime&quot;<br>
<br>
Answer SHOULD have been &quot;Ok, since we're giving druids and shamans the ability to replace you in groups, you will be given the following mana efficient spells to help you generate experience during those times when groups are hard to come by&quot;<br>
<br>
Answer WAS:  &quot;No, you're still the best healers, so live with it&quot;<br>
<br>
We've seen what this has done with clerics, as time and time again, shamans are the class of choice for duo/group healing, and Clerics have been relegated to being &quot;My 2-boxed toon&quot;.<br>
<br>
Pally/SK:  &quot;We are too weak, we have too few HP, not enough mana, and can neither solo, nor find groups efficiently&quot;<br>
<br>
Answer SHOULD have been:  &quot;You certainly need some upgrades because you guys are weak, therefore you will be getting the following NON-MELEE class specific skills which will make you both more group reliable and soloable.&quot;<br>
<br>
Answer WAS: &quot;We will upgrade your MELEE, so that you can both solo, and use your current aggro generation advantage and increased defensive skills to become desirable to group with in the role of main tank in experience groups.&quot;<br>
<br>
Warriors said:  Nothing and got what they asked for, and pride themselves on taking it up the rump and being quiet about it.<br>
<br>
Monks said:  &quot;Dude we rule&quot;<br>
<br>
Thing is, the best solo classes became VERY viable, and sometimes preferred group classes, while the best group classes got no ability to move beyond grouping, or as stated earlier, the ability to control the rate at which they gain experience.<br>
<br>
And no, monks should NEVER EVER EVER be able to take a warrior's spot tanking, it's absurd.  They *should* be fragile defensively.<br>
<br>
